Node.Notes: Apparently, "sons of mankind" and "sons of man" refer to the low and the high (people of all estates). Some think that the terms are parallel and refer to the same group, however.
Probably "a man certainly cannot redeem his fellow (brother in sense of fellow man)."

Uncertain. Text has "their inner parts," which could be interpreted as "their inner (thoughts are that) ..." Most favor the text of the ancient translations "their graves" (which just flips two consonants around).

If reading "their graves," then sense is they now permanently reside in graves even though they once held title to their own lands. If "their inner (thoughts)," then actions that reflect their thoughts.
Uncertain. Tree assumes "this is the road/fate of those who trust in themselves and those following after them who approve of what they say."
Uncertain whether sense is to graze/feed on them or to shepherd them (i.e., lead them away like a shepherd leads away sheep) .

Node.Notes: Sense is he counts himself blessed/congratulates himself.
Apparently shifts to direct statement of man speaking to himself: "They (i.e., everyone/others) praise you because you do well for yourself."
""His soul" from v. 19 seems to be the subject; (feminine noun for 3rd person singular feminine verb) otherwise, verb would be second person singular, perhaps a direct address with "you.""
